[[File:ANTT, Colecção Especial, Caixa 32, doc. 40 - Rodrigo Afonso, 1394.png|thumb|A 1394 document in the Johannine script; [[Torre do Tombo National Archive]]s, [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]]] '''Johannine script''' ({{lang-pt|letra joanina}}) was a [[palaeography|historical style of handwriting]] used in the [[Chancery (medieval office)|Portuguese Royal Chancery]] starting around the reign of [[John I of Portugal|John I]] (1385–1433) that was used until the reign of [[Manuel I of Portugal|Manuel I]] (1495–1521). It is, thus, a national variation of [[chancery hand]], a form of [[blackletter]].
Johannine script is essentially cursive, with a short [[x-height|corpus size]] (but with long [[ascender (typography)|ascenders]] and [[descender]]s), letters slope slightly to the right, words are clearly separated one from the other with no ligatures, [[punctuation]] is mostly absent, and [[Arabic numerals]] are not used (instead, numbers are given in full, or in [[Roman numerals]]). The shape of the letters ''v'' and ''b'' (and Roman numeral 5) are practically indistinguishable. Abbreviations are commonplace, mostly marked with an [[overline]] and/or [[superscript]].<ref name="Ferreira2011">{{cite thesis |last=Ferreira |first=Ana Cristina Pereira da Silva |date=2011 |title=Análise paleográfica de uma escrita de Chancelaria Régia: a letra joanina, 1370–1420 |type=M.A. |publisher=[[University of Lisbon]] |url=http://repositorio.ul.pt/bitstream/10451/6951/1/ulfl114808_tm.pdf |access-date=8 August 2017 }}</ref>
The prevailing script in documents from (and from the land that would eventually become) Portugal from the 8th to the 12th centuries was [[Visigothic script]]; from the mid-12th century onwards, for about a century, [[Carolingian minuscule]] and, later on, an incipient [[Gothic alphabet|Gothic script]]. From 1385 onwards, that is, after [[John I of Portugal|John I]] was crowned putting an end to the [[1383–1385 Portuguese interregnum|Portuguese Interregnum]], there is radical change in the writing style of the documents issued by the Royal Chancery: this new script (first called "Johannine script" by paleographer {{lang|pt|Eduardo Borges Nunes|italic=no}})<ref>{{cite book |last=Borges Nunes |first=Eduardo |date=1969 |title=Álbum de Paleografia Portuguesa |trans-title=Album of Portuguese Paleography |language=Portuguese |publisher=Instituto de Alta Cultura, Centro de Estudos Históricos |volume=vol. I }}</ref> has influences of the French {{lang|fr|[[bastarda|lettre bâtarde]]}} and Gothic scripts.
Notable scribes who wrote mostly on Johannine script include {{lang|pt|Álvaro Gonçalves|italic=no}} ({{floruit|1385–1401|pfx-lk=on}}), {{lang|pt|Gonçalo Caldeira|italic=no}} ({{floruit|1386–1426}}), and {{lang|pt|João de Lisboa|italic=no}} ({{floruit|1388–1431}}).<ref name="Ferreira2011"/>
