==Overview of results==

The Atlas defines several major dialect regions on the basis of distinctive phonological patterns and sound changes taking place in them—often [[chain shift]]s among the vowel phonemes. Major regions include:
* [[Inland Northern American English|The North]], characterized by the [[Northern Cities Vowel Shift]]
* [[Canadian English|Canada]], characterized by the [[Canadian Vowel Shift]]
* Several [[New England English|dialects in New England]], characterized by different combinations of the [[cot-caught merger]] and [[rhoticity in English|non-rhoticity]]
* [[New York City English|New York City]], characterized by non-rhoticity and a complex pattern of [[æ-tensing]]
* [[Mid-Atlantic American English|The Mid-Atlantic region]], including [[Philadelphia English|Philadelphia]] and [[Baltimore English|Baltimore]], characterized by complex æ-tensing, rhoticity, and the fronting of the back vowels /aw/, /ow/, /uw/
* [[Southern American English|The South]], characterized by monophthongization of /ay/ and resulting Southern Vowel Shift
* [[Midland American English|The Midland]], characterized by the fronting of back vowels without the monophthongization of /ay/
* [[Western American English|The West]], characterized by ''cot''-''caught'' merger and the absence of the distinctive features of the adjacent regions

On the basis of changes such as the Northern Cities Vowel Shift and the Canadian Shift, the Atlas concludes that regions are becoming more dissimilar to each other, and thus the dialect diversity of North America is increasing.

